The year 1841 produced no fewer than three editions of the Dzhlogue, ,

those of Hess,Tross, and Pabst. The two editors first named do not grapple with the question of authorship, though their work was of value in other respects; but Pabst earne forward as an uncompromising champion of

. the Tacitean tradition, dwelling not only on correspondences between the

Dialogus and the historical books in regard to the use of words and figures, &c., but also on the tone of regret for bye-gone times, and the lament over the decay of morals which readers of Tacitus at once recognize as so characteristic of his mental attitude. Seven years later, the appearance of a pamphlet by A. Dupre¹ brought Guttnann again into the field, without eliciting, however, anything of weight on the negative side except a renewal of the contention that it would have been impossible for an author who had written and published the Dialogus before or during the early part of Domitian’s reign to have lived safely through the horrors of his administration. Bernhardy, the historian of Roman literature, sided with the opposition, arguing that the points of resemblance between the Drhlogue and the other writings of Tacitus were unimportant when compared with the points of difference,and that the latter proved more than the former ¹. At this stage of the controversy (1857) Fr. Weinlraull produced the firstfruits of those exhaustive labours which entitle him to the credit of having furnished scholars with much of the

material necessary for its settlement⁸. The divergencies from the later style of Tacitus he explained by reference to the character of the historian's early studies, and to the eareful imitation of Cicero which both he and his friend Pliny the Younger seem to have prescribed for themselves; and founding not only on the general tone of the treatise but also on a laborious and detailed examination of its language and style, he

concluded that the Dialogue was a genuine work of Tacitus, composed probably in the early part of Domitian's reign.
